[[Category:George Orwell]] [[Category:Nineteen Eighty-Four]] [[Category:Freedom of expression]] [[Category:Censorship]] [[Category:Totalitarianism]]

In [[psychology]], '''prospection''' is the generation and evaluation of mental representations of possible futures. The term therefore captures a wide array of future-oriented psychological phenomena, including the prediction of future emotion ([[affective forecasting]]), the imagination of future scenarios (episodic foresight), and [[planning]]. Prospection is central to various aspects of human [[cognition]] and [[motivation]]. [[Daniel Gilbert (psychologist)]] and [[Timothy Wilson]] coined the term in 2007.<ref name=pmid17823345 "Prospection: Experiencing the Future">{{cite journal | vauthors = Gilbert DT, Wilson TD | title = Prospection: Experiencing the future | journal = Science | volume = 317 | issue = 5843 | pages = 1351-1354 | date = Sep 2007 | pmid = 17823345 }}</ref> It has since become a central area of enquiry in the [[cognitive sciences]] <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Seligman |first1=Martin E. P. |last2=Railton |first2=Peter |last3=Baumeister |first3=Roy F. |last4=Sripada |first4=Chandra |title=Navigating Into the Future or Driven by the Past |journal=Perspectives on Psychological Science |date=27 February 2013 |volume=8 |issue=2 |pages=119–141 |doi=10.1177/1745691612474317 |language=en |issn=1745-6916}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Szpunar |first1=Karl K. |last2=Spreng |first2=R. Nathan |last3=Schacter |first3=Daniel L. |title=A taxonomy of prospection: Introducing an organizational framework for future-oriented cognition: Fig. 1. |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |date=30 December 2014 |volume=111 |issue=52 |pages=18414–18421 |doi=10.1073/pnas.1417144111}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Suddendorf |first1=T |last2=Bulley |first2=A |last3=Miloyan |first3=B |title=Prospection and natural selection |journal=Current Opinion in Behavioral Sciences |date=December 2018 |volume=24 |pages=26–31 |doi=10.1016/j.cobeha.2018.01.019}}</ref>
== Prospection and learning ==
Even fundamental [[learning]] processes are, in some sense, forms of prospection <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Suddendorf |first1=Thomas |last2=Corballis |first2=Michael C. |title=The evolution of foresight: What is mental time travel, and is it unique to humans? |journal=Behavioral and Brain Sciences |date=29 October 2007 |volume=30 |issue=03 |doi=10.1017/S0140525X07001975}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gilbert |first1=D. T. |last2=Wilson |first2=T. D. |title=Prospection: Experiencing the Future |journal=Science |date=7 September 2007 |volume=317 |issue=5843 |pages=1351–1354 |doi=10.1126/science.1144161}}</ref>. [[Associative learning]] enables individual animals to track local regularities in their environments and adapt their behaviour accordingly, in order to maximise their chances of positive outcomes and minimise risks. Animals that are capable of positive and negative states (for example pleasure and pain) can eventually learn about the consequences of their actions and thereby predict imminent rewards and punishments before they occur. This enables animals to change their current actions accordingly in line with prospective consequences.
== Relationship with mental time travel == {{Main|Mental time travel}}
[[Mental time travel]] refers to the ability to mentally reconstruct personal events from the past (known as [[episodic memory]]), as well as to imagine personal future events (known as episodic foresight). Mental time travel into the future (episodic foresight or episodic future thinking) is therefore one of several types of ‘prospection’ that refers to the capacity to simulate or imagine personal future events <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Suddendorf |first1=T. |last2=Corballis |first2=M. C. |title=Mental time travel and the evolution of the human mind |journal=Genetic, Social, and General Psychology Monographs |date=1997 |volume=123 |issue=2 |pages=133–167 |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9204544 |issn=8756-7547}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Szpunar |first1=Karl K. |last2=Spreng |first2=R. Nathan |last3=Schacter |first3=Daniel L. |title=A taxonomy of prospection: Introducing an organizational framework for future-oriented cognition: Fig. 1. |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |date=30 December 2014 |volume=111 |issue=52 |pages=18414–18421 |doi=10.1073/pnas.1417144111}}</ref>.
== Examples of the functions of prospection ==
=== Episodic foresight === {{Main|Foresight (psychology)}} Episodic foresight is the capacity to imagine personal future scenarios and shape current action accordingly <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Suddendorf |first1=Thomas |last2=Moore |first2=Chris |title=Introduction to the special issue: The development of episodic foresight |journal=Cognitive Development |date=October 2011 |volume=26 |issue=4 |pages=295–298 |doi=10.1016/j.cogdev.2011.09.001}}</ref>.
=== Predicting future emotions (affective forecasting) === {{Main|Affective forecasting}}
The feelings evoked during episodic foresight enable people to infer how they would really feel if the event were to happen in reality. This thereby enables people to anticipate whether future events are desirable or undesirable, and ability called ‘[[affective forecasting]]’<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Wilson |first1=Timothy D. |last2=Gilbert |first2=Daniel T. |title=Affective Forecasting |journal=Current Directions in Psychological Science |date=23 June 2016 |volume=14 |issue=3 |pages=131–134 |doi=10.1111/j.0963-7214.2005.00355.x}}</ref>.
=== Prospective intentions === {{Main|Prospective memory}}
Simulating the future enables people to create intentions for future actions. [[Prospective memory]] is the form of memory that involves remembering to perform these planned intentions, or to recall them at some future point in time <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Einstein |first1=Gilles O. |last2=McDaniel |first2=Mark A. |title=Normal aging and prospective memory. |journal=Journal of Experimental Psychology: Learning, Memory, and Cognition |date=1990 |volume=16 |issue=4 |pages=717–726 |doi=10.1037/0278-7393.16.4.717}}</ref>. Prospective memory tasks are common in everyday life, ranging from remembering to post a letter to remembering to take one’s medication.
=== Deliberate practice === {{Main|Practice (learning method)}}
People anticipate that it is possible to shape their future self. To acquire new knowledge or additional skills, people therefore engage in repeated actions driven by the goal to improve these future capacities. This deliberate practice is essential not only for elite performance but also in the acquirement of numerous everyday feats.
=== Flexible decision-making === {{Main|Intertemporal choice}}
[[Intertemporal choice|Intertemporal choices]] are choices with outcomes that play out over time <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Berns |first1=Gregory S. |last2=Laibson |first2=David |last3=Loewenstein |first3=George |title=Intertemporal choice – toward an integrative framework |journal=Trends in Cognitive Sciences |date=November 2007 |volume=11 |issue=11 |pages=482–488 |doi=10.1016/j.tics.2007.08.011}}</ref>. Such decisions are ubiquitous in everyday life, ranging from routine decisions about what to eat for lunch (i.e. whether to adhere to a diet) to more profound decisions about [[climate change]] (i.e. whether to reduce current energy expenditure to avoid delayed costs). The ability to imagine future scenarios and adjust decisions accordingly may be important for making intertemporal choices in a flexible manner that accords with delayed consequences. Accumulating evidence suggests that cuing people to imagine the future in vivid detail can encourage preferences for delayed outcomes over immediate ones <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bulley |first1=Adam |last2=Henry |first2=Julie |last3=Suddendorf |first3=Thomas |title=Prospection and the present moment: The role of episodic foresight in intertemporal choices between immediate and delayed rewards. |journal=Review of General Psychology |date=2016 |volume=20 |issue=1 |pages=29–47 |doi=10.1037/gpr0000061}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Rung |first1=Jillian M. |last2=Madden |first2=Gregory J. |title=Experimental reductions of delay discounting and impulsive choice: A systematic review and meta-analysis. |journal=Journal of Experimental Psychology: General |date=September 2018 |volume=147 |issue=9 |pages=1349–1381 |doi=10.1037/xge0000462}}</ref>. This has been extended into real-world decisions such as in reducing the consumption of high-calorie food <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Dassen |first1=Fania C.M. |last2=Jansen |first2=Anita |last3=Nederkoorn |first3=Chantal |last4=Houben |first4=Katrijn |title=Focus on the future: Episodic future thinking reduces discount rate and snacking |journal=Appetite |date=January 2016 |volume=96 |pages=327–332 |doi=10.1016/j.appet.2015.09.032}}</ref> and increasing pro-environmental behaviours<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lee |first1=Pei-Shan |last2=Sung |first2=Yu-Hsien |last3=Wu |first3=Chia-Chun |last4=Ho |first4=Liang-Chu |last5=Chiou |first5=Wen-Bin |title=Using Episodic Future Thinking to Pre-Experience Climate Change Increases Pro-Environmental Behavior |journal=Environment and Behavior |date=26 July 2018 |pages=001391651879059 |doi=10.1177/0013916518790590}}</ref>.
== Clinical impairment ==
In recent years there have been a range of investigations into variation in prospection and its functions in clinical populations. Deficits to the mechanisms and functions of prospection have been observed in [[Alzheimer’s disease]] and other age-related [[dementias]]<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Irish |first1=Muireann |last2=Piolino |first2=Pascale |title=Impaired capacity for prospection in the dementias - Theoretical and clinical implications |journal=British Journal of Clinical Psychology |date=March 2016 |volume=55 |issue=1 |pages=49–68 |doi=10.1111/bjc.12090}}</ref>, [[Schizophrenia]], and after brain damage (especially to the [[medial temporal lobe|medial temporal lobes]])<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Henry |first1=Julie D. |last2=Addis |first2=Donna Rose |last3=Suddendorf |first3=Thomas |last4=Rendell |first4=Peter G. |title=Introduction to the Special Issue: Prospection difficulties in clinical populations |journal=British Journal of Clinical Psychology |date=March 2016 |volume=55 |issue=1 |pages=1–3 |doi=10.1111/bjc.12108}}</ref>.
Shifts in the content and modes of prospection have been observed in [[affective disorders]]<ref>{{cite journal |last1=MacLeod |first1=Andrew |title=Prospection, well-being and memory |journal=Memory Studies |date=30 June 2016 |volume=9 |issue=3 |pages=266–274 |doi=10.1177/1750698016645233}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Roepke |first1=Ann Marie |last2=Seligman |first2=Martin E. P. |title=Depression and prospection |journal=British Journal of Clinical Psychology |date=March 2016 |volume=55 |issue=1 |pages=23–48 |doi=10.1111/bjc.12087}}</ref>. For example, in both clinical [[depression (mood)|depression]] and [[anxiety]] there is an overrepresentation of possible negative future events. In depression, there is additionally a reduction in the generation of possible positive future events. There are also a range of changes to the representational format (i.e. whether people tend to represent the future in [[episodic memory|episodic]] or [[semantic]] detail) in affective disorders <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Miloyan |first1=Beyon |last2=Pachana |first2=Nancy A. |last3=Suddendorf |first3=Thomas |title=The future is here: A review of foresight systems in anxiety and depression |journal=Cognition and Emotion |date=9 December 2013 |volume=28 |issue=5 |pages=795–810 |doi=10.1080/02699931.2013.863179}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bulley |first1=Adam |last2=Henry |first2=Julie D. |last3=Suddendorf |first3=Thomas |title=Thinking about threats: Memory and prospection in human threat management |journal=Consciousness and Cognition |date=March 2017 |volume=49 |pages=53–69 |doi=10.1016/j.concog.2017.01.005}}</ref>.
